Commit Message: [vda] Allow arbitrary types for the criteria.
[tests.pktps] Added a test of a large, randomly generated order.

[pktps] Use Warshall's algorithm for updating.

It's more concise, but even slower.

[pktps] Apply Warshall's algorithm incrementally.

This seems to be the fastest approach.
Moved some input-checking from artiruno.vda to artiruno.pktps.

[pktps] Renamed `set` to `_set`.

It's only supposed to be used internally. `learn` is the external interface.
Re-construed PKTPSes as ordinary preordered sets.
[preorder] Allow the user to initialize the relations.
Allow importing from `artiruno` directly, without submodules.
[vda] Moved some code into a new function.
[__init__] Ensure submodules can be accessed from outside.
[tests.vda] Test the rule of dominance and other assumptions.
[preorder] Defend against overloaded `==` in one case.
[preorder] Made preorders mutable in the elements, not just the relations.

[vda] Add items to the preferences preorder as needed.

This change increases speed and allows the use of item spaces that would be too large to represent explicitly.
[tests.vda] Test that Artiruno can consistently find maxima.
[vda] Ensure that renaming criterion values doesn't change what questions are asked.

[vda] Fixed enforcement of the rule of dominance.

This bug was a regression caused by 49df8d2fa0cb1a7bed4f1a68e79959734f5744be.
[vda] Assume the rule of irrelevant criteria.

[vda] Don't ask about criteria on which the compared alternatives are equal.

This should reduce the number of questions asked without changing conclusions.

[tests.vda] test_appendixD: Small cleanup.

The removed assertion isn't necessary because `tuple.index` already raises an error in this case.
[conftest] Allow marking and skipping slow tests.
[vda] Don't do additional inferences in `learn` for now.
[vda] Use a central inference rule more like Larichev and Moshkovieh's (1995).
[vda] Allow deviation from the reference on more than one criterion.

[tests.vda] Deleted `test_conclusivity` for now.

This may now require multilevel mode, and I don't want to keep track of question numbers while I'm working on correctness.
[tests.vda] Added more tests of lexicographic preferences.
[tests.vda] test_recode_criteria: Use a larger `max_level` to test more diverse maxima.
[README] Explain how to run the slow tests.
[tests.vda] Added a test of one-criterion problems.
[tests.vda] Added a test where the maximum dominates.

[vda] Refined multiple deviation.

Now, instead of getting 1 deviant criterion vs. 1, 2 vs. 2, 3 vs. 3, and so on, you get 1 vs. 1, 2 vs. 1, 3 vs. 1, 2 vs. 2, and so on.
[tests.vda] Marked another test as slow, since Artiruno asks more questions now.

[tests.vda] Fixed and refactored `test_lex_generalized`.

Under Goal.FIND_BEST, I was checking `prefs` against itself instead of checking it against the asker. Whoops.
[tests.vda] Added `random_scenario` tests with an additive value function.

[tests.vda] test_value_function: Use discrete values.

Thus, we'll create some situations in which distinct vectors are equally preferable.
[tests.vda] test_recode_criteria: Changed to a set of alts that fails.

[tests.vda] test_recode_criteria: Removed the irrelevant-criterion part.

It looks like there isn't a general way to get this invariance for Artiruno without adding a lot of items to the preorder, which is impractical for big item spaces. I could add special handling of the case where there are criteria on which all alternatives are the same, but this wouldn't be useful in practice, because generally, users won't include such criteria.
[tests.vda] Test the number of questions asked.

[vda] Made foci fancier.

But as you can see from the tests, this change isn't very helpful.

[vda] Removed foci altogether.

Question numbers seem best overall without foci, and the algorithm is simpler without them.
[vda] Small refactoring of the inner loop.
[vda] Removed the nonsensical default argument for `criteria`.
[preorder] Generalized `extrema` to allow finding the `n` most extreme items.
[vda] Allow searching for the `n` best items.
[preorder] Allow naming the elements in the graph.
[interactive] Use `mktemp` to decide where to save the graph.

[vda] Don't make duplicate `allowed_pairs`.

This speeds up `pytest --slow` a good amount.
Interactively, print a message when `allowed_pairs` advances.
[vda] Allow aborting the procedure and showing what conclusions were reached so far.
Added a web interface using Brython.
[web] Made handling of the loading message more reliable.
[web] Changed the <noscript> to a performance warning.
Represent relations as an `enum` instead of plain `int`s.
[interactive] Highlight non-equal criterion values, like artiruno.web.
Factored out common parts of the two interactive interfaces.
In interactive mode, show results appropriate for `find_best`.
[interactive] Name the string parameter in uppercase.
In Python code, prefer single quotes to double quotes.

Changed RNG seeding in tests.

A future version of Python will remove the ability to seed with tuples.

[vda] Make `vda` with metaprogramming instead of wrapping.

This allows `vda` to be called with no involvement of async stuff anywhere, which simplifies testing on Brython and Pyodide.

As a bonus, `vda` now has `avda`'s parameter list.

[test_preorder] Put a `return` back in.

This effectively reverts commit 8b1f978b19b77a1c4d52c5bac4fed4d37cad4072.

I forgot that the return value is used by `graph_example`.
[preorder] Removed an old Brython bug workaround.
Use Pyodide instead of Brython for the web interface.
[web] Rearranged code and added header comments.
Use a smaller code archive for Pyodide.
[web] Show errors that occur during setup.
Extended web code to support the experimental task.
[web] Show a traceback for errors thrown during web VDA.
[interactive] Provide more verbose results text when `find_best = 1`.
[web] Fixed a typo in a button label.
[web] Run a callback after VDA is done.
[pyodide_testing] Save the Git commit hash in the code archive.
[web] Record a little more timing data.
[pyodide_testing] Added a `quiet` option for use by `runpy`.

[vda] Fixed the selection of top-n sets.

Because of how `to_try` is filtered, the old, incorrect check was mostly equivalent to what I intended, but it entailed needless iterations with `find_best > 1`.
